Certainly! The CSS Box Model is a fundamental concept that describes the layout of elements on a web page. It consists of content, padding, border, and margin. Here's an
example of the CSS Box Model in action:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>CSS Box Model Example</title>
    <style>
        /* Apply a box model to the container */
        .container {
            width: 300px;
            margin: 20px;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 2px solid #333;
        }

        /* Style the content inside the container */
        .content {
            background-color: #f9f9f9;
            padding: 20px;
        }

        /* Style the heading inside the content */
        h2 {
            color: #333;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <!-- Container with Box Model -->
    <div class="container">
        <div class="content">
            <h2>Box Model Example</h2>
            <p>This is an example demonstrating the CSS Box Model.</p>
            <p>Content inside the container has padding, border, and a specified width.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

</body>
</html>
